text: Discussion of absolute conﬁguration for bioactive Griseusins by comparing computed optical rotations and electronic circular dichroism with the experimental results Hua-Jie Zhu a, *, Wen-Xin Li a, Dong-Bao Hu b, Meng-Liang Wen c a Chinese Center for Chirality, Key Laboratory of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Diagnostics of Ministry of Education, Key Disciplines of Biotechnology Engineering of Hebei Province, Baoding 071002, China b The State Key Laboratory of Phytochemistry and Plant Resources in West China, Kunming Institute of Botany, Kunming 650204, China c Key Laboratory of Medicinal Chemistry for Natural Resources, Ministry of Education, Yunnan University, Kunming, China Article history: Received 1 July 2014 Received in revised form 25 August 2014 Accepted 9 September 2014 Available online 16 September 2014 Keywords: DFT Optical rotation Electron circular dichroism Absolute conﬁguration Griseusins

Bioactive Griseusins are large of family, they can be obtained by ferment solution of Nocardiopsis sp. or other species.1,2 Many syn- theses of Griseusins have been achieved in different research groups.3 Until now, new bioactive compounds are continuing to be found from ferment since the ﬁrst report in 1976. For example, compound 1,4 which was obtained from Nocardiopsis sp. and identiﬁed as (2S,10R,30R,40S,60R) absolute conﬁguration (AC), re- vising the earlier results.5 However, the ACs of C-2a and C-8a were not identiﬁed out. Compound 2 was obtained by synthesis. In a recent study, 3 was obtained from the same species with similar relative conﬁguration and showed strong cytotoxicity against hu- man leukemia cells (HL60) and modest cytotoxicity against human lung denocarcinoma cell lines (AGZY) with IC50 values of 0.23 and 19.6 mg/ml, respectively.6 Based on the achievements in AC de- termination using quantum methods in different research groups and ours,7e17 we decided to investigate the AC of C-2a and C-8a for http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2014.09.032 0040-4020/(cid:1) 2014 Elsevier Ltd. Absolute conﬁgurations of seven bioactive natural Griseusins were investigated. Optical rotation and the B3LYP/6-311þþG(2d,p)//PCM/B3LYP/6- electronic 311þþG(2d,p) or other levels in the gas phase and/or in solution. Computational results exhibited that the early reported absolute conﬁguration of four among the seven may not be the best structures after comparing the computed optical rotations, electron circular dichroisms to the experimental data. Then four favorable structures are suggested based on the comparison of predicted optical rotations and electronic circular dichroisms to the experimental results. It is the ﬁrst time to ﬁnd that the different position of carbonyl group on aromatic ring (planar structure changes) in Griseusins can lead to the ECD curve reversed instead of the stereogenic center changes. In traditional opinion, ECD curve reversal happens only when stereogenic center conﬁguration reverses, such as from AC of (R) to (S). Contents lists available at ScienceDirect Tetrahedron 70 (2014) 8236e8243 compounds 1 theoretically using optical rotation (OR) and elec- tronic circular dichroism (ECD) spectra. Notice, since there is a hy- droxyl on C-9 in 3, even if the substituent on C-19 is toward the front, which is reversed to 1 and 2, its conﬁguration is still (S). Also the O of ether of sugar moiety is towards the front in 1 and 2, however, it is backwards in 3, and this leads to the C-60 and C-30 having (S) conﬁguration.

Compounds 4 to 7 were listed in the same reports. Again, it should be noticed here that C-10 in 7 is assigned as (S) AC when the group of eCH2CO2H has the same orientation on C-10 since there isn’t an O on C-9; it is assigned as (R) AC on C-10 in 4 to 6. Com- pound 5 showed pronounced cytotoxic potency (mean IC50: 0.43 uM) combined with a signiﬁcant selectivity for mammary cancer, (cid:1) 2014 Elsevier Ltd. After careful examinations of all possible structures for 1, 3, 4, 5, 6, and 7 by comparing their computed OR magnitudes and ECD spectra with the experimental data, more reasonable structures are proposed for 1, 4, 5, and 6. 1.1. Computational methods and results Currently, computational methods have been used more and more widely in determining or investigating AC for chiral com- pounds, especially for nature products. It has provided many ben- eﬁts in our research group and other groups.7e18 In this theoretical study, OR and ECD were computed using density functional theory (DFT) at different basis sets. Gaussian 03 software package was used in calculations.19 1.2. Computational methods

Conformational searches were performed using MMFF94S force ﬁeld for all compounds except for 2 that was not investigated in this study. All geometries with relative energy from 0 to 7 kcal/mol were used in optimizations at the B3LYP/6-31G(d) level ﬁrst. The B3LYP/6-31G(d)-optimized conformers with relative energy from 0 to 2.5 kcal/mol were further used in OR computations at the B3LYP/6-311þþG(2d,p) level in the gas phase. Single point energy (SPE) corrections for all geometries were performed at the B3LYP/ aug-cc-pVDZ level in solutions using PCM. The SPEs were further used in OR computations. The whole molecular OR values were obtained via Boltzmann sum by using all conformational OR values. The B3LYP/6-31G(d)-optimized conformers with relative energy from 0 to 2.5 kcal/mol were then re-optimized at Fig. 1. Whole procedure for OR computations of compounds 1, 3e7. H.-J. Zhu et al. / Tetrahedron 70 (2014) 8236e8243 the B3LYP/6-31þG(d,p) level in the gas phase and at the B3LYP/ 6-311þþG(2d,p) re- spectively. These conformers were used in OR computations at the B3LYP/6-311þþG(2d,p) level in the gas phase again (Fig. 1). ECD computations for all compounds were carried out at the B3LYP/6-311þþG(2d,p)//B3LYP/6-31þG(d,p) level in the gas phase. Boltzmann statistics were performed for ECD simulations. The bands were then expanded using Harada-Nakanishi equation,20 standard deviation of s was 0.4 eV in simulations. 2. Results and discussion

The data of OR and ECD of 1 were reported, 2 had almost the same AC as 1’s except for C-40. Thus, 1 was selected for OR and ECD computations ﬁrst. Compound 1 has either AC of 1A or 1B. Relative conﬁguration of compound 3 was assigned by X-ray study and therefore 3 was selected as a ‘model compound’ to test the com- putational methods whether are suitable or not in predictions of OR and ECD for 1. The predicted ORs (from (cid:2)18.6 to (cid:2)61.8) for (2S,9S,10S,30S,60S)-3 have good agreements with the experimental OR ((cid:2)68), most of the computed OR magnitudes were from (cid:2)33 to (cid:2)62 using different methods. Especially, both methods 3 and 5 predicted OR values of (cid:2)61.8 that is very close to the experimental OR of (cid:2)68. The relative conﬁguration of 3 was well established using X-ray experiments, the predicted negative ORs from (cid:2)33 to (cid:2)62 exhibited that com- pound ((cid:2))-3 should have the AC of (2S,9S,10S,30S,60S).

However, the ORs computed for 1A or 1B were both negative except for a þ10.8 for 1B using method 5. This indicated (þ)-1 might be one of the enantiomers of (2aR,2S,8aS,10S,30R,40S,60R)-1A or (2aS,2S,8aR,10S,30R,40S,60R)-1B, namely, it could be either ACs of (2aS,2R,8aR,10R,30S,40R,60S) or (2aR,2R,8aS,10R,30S,40R,60S). This is different from the previous reports.4 Therefore, ECD was computed for 1A and 1B at the B3LYP/6-311þþG(2d,p)//B3LYP/6-31þG(d,p) level (Fig. 2), respectively. The ECD predicted for (2aS,2S,8aR,10S,30R,40S,60R)-1B looks very similar with the experimental ECD. It hints that 1 should have (2aS,2S,8aR,10S,30R,40S,60R)-1B structure. However, almost all of the ORs calculated for 1B were negative from (cid:2)15 to (cid:2)23 except for OR of þ10 using method 5. This meant 1 should be AC of the en- antiomer of 1B. The two different methods predicted a conﬂict conclusion. The predicted ECD for 1A looked like a ‘mirror’ imag- ine of experimental ECD, this hinted that 1 may have (2aS,2R,8aS,10S,30S,40R,60S)-1A structure. This agreed with the conclusion from OR. However, this is different from the original result.4 As mentioned above, when 3 was used as ‘inner standard’ to evaluate the reliability of DFT methods selected in the study, the current results might be reliable. In our recent study, the conclusion from OR and ECD had good agreements for rigid chiral compounds.21 Especially the predictions for assignment of ((cid:2))-brevianamides from (2S,13S) to (2R,13R) had good agreement with the experimental results using OR and ECD methods.21c In current study, the conclusion from the computed OR is different from that of ECD. The reported structure may exist some unfavorable conﬁgurations. It should be important to re-examine the structures 4 to 6. Should product 6 have the similar structures like 14 or 15 in- stead of 10? This is unknown until now. Thus, ORs for both 14 and 15 were investigated using the same two methods as used in computations of OR and ECD for 13. The predicted OR for (2R,9R,10R,30R,40R,60R)-14 was only þ86.8 and þ106.6 (Table 4). The OR for 15 were þ26.8 and þ28.1, respectively. All the OR data are much smaller than the experimental result ((cid:2)198, Table 4). In contrast, 10’s OR magnitudes predicted are (cid:2)143.9 and (cid:2)141.6 us- ing the same two methods, respectively. Based on the fact that the methods used have well predicted the OR values mentioned above, it suggested that 10 be the favorite candidate for correction for 6. Further ECD study for 14 and 15, which were obtained at the B3LYP/6-311þþG(2d,p)//B3LYP/6-31þG(d,p) level, showed similar ECD curve as those of 12 and 13 (Fig. 8). Again, this exhibited that the position of the C]O and CeOH on the aromatic ring have big effect on Cotton effect in ECD study. There is other possibilities existed for 4 to 6. Now, the three favorable structures, enantiomers of 13 and 12, and compound 10 are suggested for corrections for 4 to 6, re- spectively. We have to go back to see the structural identiﬁcations of 1. The re-investigation principle is that we ignore the evidences observed from NOE between the H60 and H10. Possible structures (2aR,2S,8aS,10S,30S,40R,60S)-19A and (2aS,2S,8aR,10S,30S,40R,60S)- 19B are desired as the favorites for corrections for 1A and 1B, re- spectively. The same ﬁve computational methods as mentioned at the beginning time are used in OR computations for 19A and 19B, respectively (Table 6).

The OR magnitudes obtained for the two possible geometries exhibited that the enantiomer of 19A is a more reasonable structure for correction for 1A. The current OR magnitudes and sign exhibits that (þ)-19 should have AC of (2aS,2R,8aR,10R,30R,40S,60R). Pre- dicted absolute values of OR for (2aS,2S,8aR,10S,30S,40R,60S)-19B is much bigger than the experimental results, it hints that this is not a good candidate for correction for 1, or 1 should have the AC of enantiomer of 19B. To further conclude one of the possible struc- tures, ECD computations were performed for both 19A and 19B, respectively. ECD computations for (2aR,2S,8aS,10S,30S,40R,60S)-19A and (2aS,2S,8aR, 10S,30S,40R,60S)-19B were performed at the B3LYP/6- 311þþG(2d,p) level in the gas phase, respectively, and the ECD spectra are illustrated in Fig. 10. It was found that the curve of predicted ECD for (2aR,2S,8aS,10S,30S,40R,60S)-19A looks like a mirror-imagine of the experimental ECD (Fig. 10, left). It hints that the enantiomer of 19A should be the favorite for correction for 1A. This conclusion agrees to that from OR data. Until now, all the correction structures, 19A, 13, 12, and 10 look reasonable for the corrections for products 1, 4, 5, and 6, re- spectively. However, there is a ﬁnal possibility that was not ex- cluded. The structure such as 1C, which can be transferred from 1A may exist theoretically, 19A could convert to 19C too. Therefore, if 1C is excluded, then 19C is also excluded. After conformational searches using MMFF94S force ﬁeld, the low energy conformations with 0e10 kcal/mol was used in optimization at the B3LYP/6-31G(d) level in the gas phase. The new conformers with energy from 0 to 2.5 kcal/mol were further optimized at the B3LYP/ 6-311þG(d) level in the gas phase based our recent reports.21 It was found that 1C had about 25.4 kcal/mol higher than the corre- sponding 1A in GFE. This indicated that the quantity of 1C in solution can be ignored. Namely, 19C could be excluded too. Therefore, the structures (2R,9R,10R,30R,40R,60R)-10, (2aS,8aR,2R,10R,30S,40R,60S)- (2S,9S,10S,30S,40R,60S)-21 (enantio 20 (enantiomer of 19A), mer of 13), and (2S,9S,10S,30S,60S)-22 (enantiomer of 12), which are favorable corrections for 6, 1, 4, and 5, are illustrated below.

Combinational use of OR and ECD is necessary in stereochemistry study for complex natural products when there is no X-ray study. The theoretical method, B3LYP/6-311þþG(2d,p)//B3LYP/6- current 31þG(d,p), can provide relatively accurate results in AC study for such kind of big family compounds study. It is important to point out that the different position of >C]O group on aromatic ring can cause the ECD curve reversed without the changes of stereogenic center. H.J.
